item.title: Metals Inch Higher as Dollar Slides
item.description: Metals prices were rising in early London trading as a sliding dollar helped boost commodities.

item.title: Dollar Falls as Stocks Rebound
item.description: The safe-haven dollar turned lower after stocks rebounded, but MUFG expects the currency to remain supported, given a mostly risk-averse environment.

item.title: Honda More Than Doubled First-Quarter Net Profit as Car Business Recovered
item.description: Honda Motor’s first-quarter net profit more than doubled from a year earlier, driven by a sharp recovery in earnings at its car business as the chip shortage eased.

item.title: TUI Swings to Profit
item.description: TUI reported an underlying Ebit of €169.4 million in the third quarter, and said its summer bookings were at 95% of the level seen pre-pandemic.

item.title: Sony Group's First-Quarter Net Hurt by Weaker Movie, Financial Earnings
item.description: Sony Group’s first-quarter net profit fell 17% from a year earlier due to weaker earnings from movie and financial businesses.

item.title: Vestas Earnings Miss Views but Maintains Guidance
item.description: Vestas posted a larger-than-expected net loss of €115 million in the second quarter but backed its full-year guidance after seeing strong growth in its service business.

item.title: Nikkei Falls 0.53%, Dragged by Financial Stocks
item.description: Japanese stocks ended lower, dragged by falls in financial stocks, as concerns resurface about the health of the U.S. banking sector and domestic bond yields decline.

item.title: ABN Amro Profit, Income Beat Views
item.description: ABN Amro Bank posted second quarter operating income and net profit ahead of expectations but lowered its cost guidance for the year to €5.2 billion and doesn’t expect to reach its 2024 target of €4.7 billion.

item.title: E.ON Earnings Boosted by Drop in Wholesale Prices
item.description: E.ON raised its forecast for the full year after it reported a rise in adjusted earnings to €3 billion for the second quarter due to more stable wholesale energy prices.

item.title: Cathay Pacific Swung to Profit in First Half
item.description: Cathay Pacific Airways swung to profit in the first half of the year, benefiting from the lifting of Covid-19 curbs that pushed up passenger revenue substantially.

item.title: U.S. to Ban Some Investments in China
item.description: President Biden plans to sign an executive order that will also require U.S. private-equity and venture-capital firms to disclose certain investments in the country.

item.title: One of America's Favorite Generals Leads the Niger Coup
item.description: Brig. Gen. Moussa Salaou Barmou, long courted by Washington as a partner against Islamist extremism, has emerged as the main diplomatic channel between the U.S. and the junta.

item.title: Abortion-Rights Supporters Score Win as Ohio Voters Defeat Issue 1
item.description: The measure would have made it harder to pass amendments to the state constitution, including one on the November ballot guaranteeing abortion rights.

item.title: The Biohacking Devotees Spending Hundreds of Thousands---Even Millions---to Enhance Their Homes
item.description: Light-therapy beds. Infrared saunas. Ozone generators. These homeowners have infused health and wellness into their properties, and then some.

item.title: Germany's Tardy Trains Derail National Psyche
item.description: Chronically late Deutsche Bahn resorts to scent therapy to placate passengers; ‘this is an embarrassment, it is a cultural crisis.’

item.title: Returning Ukrainian Refugees Say There's No Place Like Home
item.description: Those who fled the country because of the war with Russia are returning, citing family reunification as a primary reason.

item.title: Ohio voters defeated a measure that would have made it harder to change the state constitution, meaning an amendment on the November ballot enshrining abortion access faces a lower bar for passage.
